{{Infobox military conflict |conflict=Battle of Erzurum |partof=the [[Ottoman–Persian War (1821–1823)]] |image= |date=1821 |place=[[Erzurum]], now in Turkey |result=Persian victory<ref>R. Ernest Dupuy and Trevor N. Dupuy, ''The Harper Encyclopedia of Military History'', 4th edition, (HarperCollins Publishers, 1993), 853.</ref> |combatant1={{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Ottoman Empire]] |combatant2=[[Image:Flag of Agha Mohammad Khan.svg|22px]] [[Qajar dynasty|Persian Empire]] |commander1={{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Mahmud II]] |commander2=[[Image:Flag of Agha Mohammad Khan.svg|22px]] [[Abbas Mirza]] |strength1=50,000 soldiers |strength2=30,000 soldiers |casualties1= |casualties2=}}
The '''Battle of Erzurum''' occurred in 1821 as part of the Ottoman-Persian War of 1821-1823. The [[Qajar dynasty|Persians]], led by crown prince [[Abbas Mirza]] himself scored a crushing defeat over their [[Ottoman Turks|Ottoman]] arch rivals near [[Erzurum]], securing a Persian victory.
The Persians were heavily outnumbered with 30,000 men, led by Crown Prince [[Abbas Mirza]], against the Turks with 50,000 men. However, the Persian army had recently been undergoing new modernisations according to the most up to date European models, with leadership of Abbas Mirza's brother, [[Dowlatshah]], as part of the modernising policy known as [[Nizam-ı Cedid|Nezām-e Jadīd]].
